Well the only time - mother always did the smacking and it - the only time I ever saw me father hit me sister was - I'd got a cut on that thumb and we - it was w
hen we were at the club at Eclles and it was duck apple night, you know, Holloween and we had a - a string rigged up, mother did it for us, well she was in the club but she used to pop in - it didn't have a licence. We used to make oxo and drinks, you kno
w, with only young men and women in it and - every now and again she would come in you see. But it would only be about {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 6}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}
{\xmlattrvalue 0}}}six o'clock{\*\xmlclose} - it was after me father had - come from the mill you see, and he'd take over and then me mother could come in for a minute or
 two but she was going - we've been a family that have been very fond of the theatre. Always. And mother had a night out and she was going to the Crown Theatre which was only practically opposite the club. We used to get tickets even when we at the shop a
t
 Patricroft - complimentary tickets. Well mother used to take me sometimes but anyway she was going with somebody else this night and we were - she left us and - threaded these apples - and it - over a bowl of water, we had to try and bite, you see. And o
f
 course, the last thing me mother said, now don't let Edna have that knife. See. Anyway I must have been busy bobbing and my sister must have thought that I was doing it to often and she pushed me out of the way and grabbed the knife, you see, she was goi
n
g to take - I thought the apple. And of course I - grabbed her and - and I must have - she did that and I lifted me hand up and of course the blood - went down. Well - I let out one scream and rushed - our house in the Eccles club was part of a very big h
o
use, there was a huge room that they called a ballroom and you had to dash across into the club room. And of course when me father saw the blood he never could stand the sight of blood, and - me mother wasn't there, she'd gone to the theatre and so I - he
 
asked one of the chappies like to look after the place and it was - snowing it was - it's October isn't it - but the winter was early and it was cold and - and he got me in - a blanket - a shawl or something, and he ran with me all the way to Patricroft h
ospital - a long way. And of course there was a - a nurse there but they made a terrible job of it, you can see can't you.
